'''Yasotakeru''' (八十梟帥) is a name appearing in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}. The term may be used to mean "numerous brave warriors." In the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft}}, the name is written as 八十建 and is used in the latter sense.

== History ==
According to the ''Nihon Shoki,'' when {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} ascended Takakurayama in {{ill|Uda|ja|宇陀|12=draft|12=draft}} to survey the land, Yasotakeru was on the hill of Kunimikashira, with women stationed on Onnazaka, men stationed on Otokozaka, and charcoal placed at Sumisaka. Yasotakeru was later defeated by the emperor and killed.

Additionally, {{ill|Otoutowaka|ja|弟猾|12=draft|12=draft}} reported, "In the land of Yamato, at the village of {{ill|Shiki|ja|磯城|12=draft|12=draft}}, there is Yasotakeru of Shiki, and at the village of Takaoha, there is Yasotakeru of Akatani."

{{ill|Otoshiki|ja|弟磯城|12=draft|12=draft}} also remarked, "Upon hearing that the children of the heavenly deities had arrived, my brother {{ill|Anishiki|ja|兄磯城|12=draft|12=draft}} gathered Yasotakeru and prepared arms and armor to fight them."

The ''Nihon Shoki'' also mentions "Yasotakeru of the {{ill|Kumaso|ja|熊襲|12=draft|12=draft}}" in the entry for the 12th year, 12th month, 5th day of {{ill|Emperor Keikō|ja|景行天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== References ==
* ''Nihon Shoki''
* ''Kojiki''

== Related topics ==
* {{ill|Rebel forces|ja|賊軍|1=zokugun|12=draft|12=draft}}


